{{distinguish|text=the [[Bangime language]] of Mali}} {{Infobox language |name=Bangi |nativename=Bobangi |states=[[Republic of Congo]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] |speakers={{sigfig|121,760|2}} |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] ([[Guthrie classification of Bantu languages#Zone C|Zone C]]) |fam6=[[Bangi–Ntomba languages|Bangi–Ntomba]] (C.30) |fam7=Bangi–Moi |dia1=Moi |dia2=Liku |dia3=Rebu |dia4=&nbsp;&nbsp; ''Derived creoles:'' |dia5=[[Lingala]] |dia6=[[Bangala language|Bangala]] |lc1=bni|ld1=Bangi |lc2=mow|ld2=Moi |guthrie=C.32 |glotto=bang1354 |glottoname=Bangi |glotto2=moic1236 |glottoname2=Moi }}
The '''Bangi language''', or '''''Bobangi''''', is a relative and main lexical source of [[Lingala]] spoken in central [[Africa]]. Dialects of the language are spoken on both sides of the [[Ubangi River]] and [[Congo River]].
== Use in trade == As the Bobangi people came to dominate the slave trade along the upper [[Congo River]] in the late 18th century, the Bangi language was used to facilitate trade between different ethnic groups in the region. Linguist John Whitehead claimed that the Moye, [[Likuba language|Likuba]], Bonga, [[Mpama people|Mpama]], Lusakani, and [[Bangala language|Bangala]] peoples all used Bangi for intercommunication in the 1890s. Traders in the region who did not speak Bangi used a trade trade language that borrowed heavily from Bangi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=River of Wealth, River of Sorrow: The Central Zaire Basin in the Era of the Slave and Ivory Trade, 1500-1891|last=Harns|first=Robert W.|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1981|isbn=0300026161|location=New Haven|pages=92-93}}</ref> At the height of indigenous trade along the upper river, the Bobangi dominated the 500 kilometer section of the Congo between the [[Kwah River]] and the equator, which most river trade passed through.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=River of Wealth, River of Sorrow|last=Harms|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=7}}</ref> Other ethnic groups in this area were either assimilated into the Bobangi ethnic alliance, adopting the Bangi language, or were driven off.<ref>{{Cite book|title=River of Wealth, River of Sorrow|last=Harms|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=129-130}}</ref> However, the Bobangi dominance over trade was ended by Europeans in the late 19th century when colonial powers pushed local indigenous groups out of profitable trade. By the late twentieth century, there were very few Bobangi people remaining in the area they had controlled a century earlier, and the Bangi language is no longer widespread.<ref name=":0" />
