{{Infobox language |name=Bozo |region=[[Mali]], [[Nigeria]] |ethnicity=[[Bozo people]] |speakers=230,000 in Mali apart from Tieyaxo |date=2003–2009 |ref = e18 |speakers2=unknown number Tieyaxo; unknown number Jenaama in Nigeria |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam1=[[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]] |fam2=[[Mande languages|Mande]] |fam3=Western Mande |fam4=Northwestern |fam5=Soninke–Bobo |fam6=Soninke–Bozo |lc1=bzx|ld1=Hainyaxo (Kɛlɛngaxo) |lc2=boo|ld2=Tiemacèwè |lc3=boz|ld3=Tiéyaxo |lc4=bze|ld4=Jenaama |glotto=bozo1252 |glottorefname=Bozo }}
'''Bozo''', or '''Boso''', meaning ''house of straw'', is a [[Mande language]] spoken by the [[Bozo people]], the principal fishing people of the [[Inner Niger Delta]] in [[Mali]]. According to the 2000 census, the Bozo people number about 132,100. The Bozo [[dialect cluster]] is often considered to be one language, but there is quite a bit of diversity. ''Ethnologue'' recognises four languages on the basis of requirements for literacy materials. Bozo is part of the northwestern branch of the Mande languages; the closest linguistic relative is [[Soninke language|Soninke]], a major language spoken in the northwestern section of southern Mali, in eastern Senegal, and in southern Mauritania. The Bozo often speak one or more regional languages such as [[Bambara language|Bamana]], [[Fulfulde language|Maasina Fulfulde]], or [[Songhay languages|Western Songhay]]. The language is [[tone language|tonal]], with three lexical tones.
The Bozo cluster is divided into the following varieties: *Hainyaxo (Hainyaho, Kɛlɛngaxo) (a few thousand speakers)<ref>The [[Ethnologue]] (15th edition) reports for both Hainyaho and Tigemaxo identical speaker counts: 117,696, from the 1987 census. In the fourteenth edition, this number was noted to be the number of 'all mother tongue Boso speakers'. ({{cite web |url=http://www.ethologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code%3DBZX |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-11-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930124841/http://www.ethologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code=BZX |archivedate=2007-09-30 |df= }}, {{cite web |url=http://www.ethnologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code%3DBOZ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-09-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060514190629/http://www.ethnologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code=BOZ |archivedate=2006-05-14 |df= }}) In the light of the 200,000 reported speakers of Sorogama, by far the most widely spoken Bozo variety, speaker numbers for Hainyaho and Tigemaxo are put at 'a few thousand' here.</ref> *Tiɛma Cɛwɛ (Tièma cièwe) (2,500 speakers in 1991) *Tiéyaxo (Tigemaxo) (a few thousand speakers) *Sorogaama (Jenaama, Sorko) (200,000 speakers in 2005)
Hainyaho, spoken by the Hain (sg. Xan), is the most western dialect, spoken in two spots along the Niger. It is most closely related to Tigemaxo, its eastern neighbour which is spoken around [[Diafarabé]]. The central and most widely spoken Bozo language is Sorogama, which actually consists of four dialects, Pondori (south of [[Mopti]]), Kotya, Korondugu (north of [[Mopti]]) and Debo (around [[Lake Debo]]). Tièma Cièwè is the northeastern most of the Bozo cluster, spoken in the vicinity of Lake Debo.
