A '''macuahuitl''' ({{IPA-nah|maːˈkʷawit͡ɬ|}}) is a wooden club with [[obsidian]] blades. The name is derived from the [[Nahuatl language]] and means "hand-wood".<ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/macuahuitl-sword-aztec-weapons-171566|title=The Fearsome Close-Quarter Combat Weapon of the Aztecs|work=ThoughtCo|access-date=27 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528134805/https://www.thoughtco.com/macuahuitl-sword-aztec-weapons-171566|archive-date=28 May 2018|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Its sides are embedded with [[prismatic blade]]s traditionally [[Obsidian use in Mesoamerica|made from obsidian]]; obsidian is capable of producing an edge sharper than high quality steel razor blades. The macuahuitl was a standard close combat weapon.

Use of the maquahuitl as a weapon is attested from the first millennium CE. By the time of the [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|Spanish conquest]] the macuahuitl was widely distributed in [[Mesoamerica]]. The weapon was used by different civilisations including the [[Aztec]] (Mexicas), [[Maya civilization|Mayan]], [[Mixtec]] and [[Toltec]].

One example of this weapon survived the [[Conquest of Mexico]]; it was part of the [[Royal Armoury of Madrid]] until it was destroyed by a fire in 1884. Images of the original designs survive in diverse catalogues. The oldest replica is the macuahuitl created by the medievalist [[Achille Jubinal]] in the 19th century.

== Description ==
[[File:Macuahuitl Armeria Real Higher Definition.png|thumb|upright=1.5|A drawing from the ''Catalog of the Royal Armoury of Madrid'' by the medievalist [[Achille Jubinal]] in the 19th century. The original specimen was destroyed by a fire in 1884.]]

The maquahuitl ({{lang-nci|mācuahuitl}}, other [[orthography|orthographic]] variants include {{lang|nci|maquahutil}}, {{lang|nci|macquahuitl}} and {{lang|nci|māccuahuitl}}),<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |url=http://whp.uoregon.edu/dictionaries/nahuatl/index.lasso?&dowhat=FindJustOne&theRecID=448227&theWord=macuahuitl. |title=Macuahuitl |editor=Stephanie Wood |encyclopedia=Nahuatl Dictionary/Diccionario del náhuatl |publisher=Wired Humanities Projects, [[University of Oregon]] |access-date=29 May 2018 }}</ref> a type of {{lang|tnq|[[macana]]}}, was a common weapon used by the [[Aztec warfare|Aztec military forces]] and other cultures of central Mexico. It was noted during the 16th-century [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire|Spanish conquest of the region]]. Other military equipment recorded includes the [[chīmalli|round shield]] ({{wikt-lang|nci|chīmalli}}, {{IPA-nah|t͡ʃiˈmalːi|}}), the [[bow and arrow|bow]] ({{lang|nci|tlahuītōlli}}, {{IPA-nah|t͡ɬaʔwiːˈtoːlːi|}}), and the [[spear-thrower]] ({{wikt-lang|nci|ahtlatl}}, {{IPA-nah|ˈaʔt͡ɬat͡ɬ|}}).<ref>Soustelle (1961), p. 209.</ref> Its sides are embedded with [[prismatic blade]]s traditionally [[obsidian use in Mesoamerica|made from obsidian]]; obsidian is capable of producing an edge sharper than high-quality steel razor blades.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Buck |first=BA |date=March 1982 |title=Ancient Technology in Contemporary Surgery |journal=The Western Journal of Medicine |volume=136 |issue=3 |pages=265–269 |pmc=1273673 |pmid=7046256 }}</ref>

It was capable of inflicting serious lacerations from the rows of [[obsidian]] blades embedded in its sides. These could be [[knapping|knapped]] into blades or spikes, or into a circular design that looked like scales.<ref>Coe (1962), p. 168.</ref> The maquahuitl is not a sword or a club, although it approximates a European broadsword.<ref name="auto"/>

[[File:Florentine Codex IX Aztec Warriors.jpg|thumb|Aztec warriors as shown in the 16th-century ''[[Florentine Codex]]'' (Vol. IX). Each warrior is brandishing a macuahuitl.]]

According to conquistador {{lang|es|[[Bernal Díaz del Castillo]]|italic=no}}, the macuahuitl was 0.91 to 1.22 m long, and 75 mm wide, with a groove along either edge, into which sharp-edged pieces of flint or obsidian were inserted and firmly fixed with an adhesive.<ref>From [[Alfred Maudslay|A. P. Maudslay]]'s translation commentary of {{lang|es|[[Bernal Díaz del Castillo]]|italic=no}}'s {{lang|es|Verdadera Historia de la Conquista de Nueva España|italic=yes}} (republished as ''The Discovery and Conquest of Mexico'', p. 465).</ref> The rows of obsidian blades were sometimes discontinuous, leaving gaps along the side, while at other times the rows were set close together and formed a single edge.<ref name="Hass85">Hassig, 1988, p. 85</ref> It was noted by the Spanish that the macuahuitl was so cleverly constructed that the blades could be neither pulled out nor broken. The macuahuitl was made with either a one-handed or two-handed grip, as well as in rectangular, ovoid, or pointed forms. Two-handed macuahuitl have been described as being "as tall as a man".<ref name="Hass83">Hassig, 1988 p. 83.</ref>

== Typology ==
According to [[National School of Anthropology and History]] (ENAH) archaeologist [[Marco Cervera Obregón]], there were two versions of this weapon: The macuahuitl, about {{convert|70|to|80|cm|in}} long with six to eight blades on each side; and the mācuāhuitzōctli, a smaller club about {{convert|50|cm|in}} long with only four obsidian blades.<ref>Cervera Obregón 2006A, p.&nbsp;128</ref>

== Specimens ==
According to [[Ross Hassig]], the last authentic macuahuitl was destroyed in 1884 in a fire in the [[Royal Armoury of Madrid|Real Armería]] in Madrid, where it was housed beside the last [[tepoztopilli]].<ref name="Hass83"/><ref>Hassig 1992, p. 169.</ref> According to Marco Cervera Obregón, there is supposed to be at least one macuahuitl in a [[Museo Nacional de Antropología]] warehouse,<ref>Cervera Obregón 2006A, p. 137</ref> but it is possibly lost.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cerevera Obregón |first=Marco |title=El macuahuitl, arqueologia experimental |url=http://arqueomilitar.blogspot.com/2009/02/el-macuahuitl-arqueologia-experimental.html |accessdate=26 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708023803/http://arqueomilitar.blogspot.com/2009/02/el-macuahuitl-arqueologia-experimental.html |archive-date=8 July 2011 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all |date=19 February 2009 }}</ref>

No actual maquahuitl specimens remain and the present knowledge of them comes from contemporaneous accounts and illustrations that date to the 16th century and earlier.<ref name="Hass85"/>

== Origins and distribution ==
[[File:Lienzo de Tlaxcala Iximche.gif|thumb|''[[History of Tlaxcala|Lienzo de Tlaxcala]]'' depiction of a battle during the [[Spanish conquest of Guatemala]]. Both [[Conquistador|Spanish]]-led [[Indian auxiliaries]] (left) as well as [[Maya peoples|Maya]] (right) wield macuahuitls.]]

The maquahuitl predates the Aztecs. Tools made from obsidian fragments were used by some of the earliest Mesoamericans. Obsidian used in ceramic vessels has been found at Aztec sites. Obsidian cutting knives, sickles, scrapers, drills, razors, and arrow points have also been found.<ref name="Smit86">Smith, 1996, p. 86</ref> Several obsidian mines were close to the Aztec civilisations in the [[Valley of Mexico]] as well as in the mountains north of the valley.<ref>Smith, 1996, p. 87</ref> Among these were the [[Sierra de las Navajas]] (Razor Mountains), named after their obsidian deposits. Use of the maquahuitl as a weapon is attested from the 1st millenia{{nbs}}CE. A Mayan carving at [[Chichen Itza]] shows a warrior holding a macuahuitl, depicted as a club having separate blades sticking out from each side. In a mural, a warrior holds a club with many blades on one side and one sharp point on the other, also a possible variant of the macuahuitl.<ref name="Hass85"/><ref name="Obregón">{{cite journal |last=Cervera Obregón |first=Marco |year=2006 |title=The macuahuitl: an innovative weapon of the Late Post-Classic in Mesoamerica |url=http://www.woosterglobalhistory.org/LAcolonial/archive/files/23395812_33c717a7fb.pdf |journal=Arms & Armour |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=137–138 |accessdate=26 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320100504/http://www.woosterglobalhistory.org/LAcolonial/archive/files/23395812_33c717a7fb.pdf |archive-date=20 March 2012 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

By the time of the [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|Spanish conquest]] the macuahuitl was widely distributed in [[Mesoamerica]], with records of its use by the Aztecs, Mixtecs, Tarascans, Toltecs and others.<ref>Obregón, 2006A, pp. 137–138</ref> It was also commonly used by the [[Indian auxiliaries]] of Spain,{{sfnp|Asselbergs|2014|pp=76, 78}} though they favored Spanish swords. As Mesoamericans in Spanish service needed a special permission to carry European arms, metal swords brought Indian auxiliaries more prestige than maquahuitls in the eyes of Europeans as well as natives.{{sfnp|Asselbergs|2014|p=79}}

== Effectiveness ==
The macuahuitl was sharp enough to decapitate a man.<ref name="Smit86"/> According to an account by [[Bernal Díaz del Castillo]], one of [[Hernán Cortés]]’s [[conquistador]]s, it could even decapitate a horse:

{{quote|[[Pedro de Morón]] was a very good horseman, and as he charged with three other horsemen into the ranks of the enemy the Indians seized hold of his lance and he was not able to drag it away, and others gave him cuts with their broadswords, and wounded him badly, and then they slashed at the mare, and cut her head off at the neck so that it hung by the skin, and she fell dead.<ref>Diaz del Castillo, p. 126</ref>}}

Another account by a companion of Cortés known as ''[[Narrative of Some Things of New Spain and of the Great City of Temestitan|The Anonymous Conqueror]]'' tells a similar story of its effectiveness:
{{quote|They have swords of this kind – of wood made like a two-handed sword, but with the hilt not so long; about three fingers in breadth. The edges are grooved, and in the grooves they insert stone knives, that cut like a [[Toledo steel|Toledo]] blade. I saw one day an Indian fighting with a mounted man, and the Indian gave the horse of his antagonist such a blow in the breast that he opened it to the entrails, and it fell dead on the spot. And the same day I saw another Indian give another horse a blow in the neck, that stretched it dead at his feet.|"Offensive and Defensive Arms", page 23<ref name="anon">The Anonymous Conqueror. (1917). [http://www.famsi.org/research/christensen/anon_con/section05.htm ''Narrative of Some Things of New Spain and of the Great City of Temestitán The Cortés Society:''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306183615/http://www.famsi.org/research/christensen/anon_con/section05.htm |date=6 March 2015 }} Chapter 4. New York.</ref>}}

Another account by [[Francisco de Aguilar (conquistador)|Francisco de Aguilar]] reads:

{{quote|They used ... cudgels and swords and a great many bows and arrows ... One Indian at a single stroke cut open the whole neck of [[Cristóbal de Olid]]’s horse, killing the horse. The Indian on the other side slashed at the second horseman and the blow cut through the horse’s [[pastern]], whereupon this horse also fell dead. As soon as this sentry gave the alarm, they all ran out with their weapons to cut us off, following us with great fury, shooting arrows, spears and stones, and wounding us with their swords. Here many Spaniards fell, some dead and some wounded, and others without any injury who fainted away from fright.<ref>Francisco de Auguilar, untitled account, in The Conquistadors, 139–140, 155.</ref>}}

[[File:Aztec Warriors (Florentine Codex).jpg|thumb|This drawing, from the 16th-century [[Florentine Codex]], shows Aztec warriors brandishing macuahuitls]]

Given the importance of [[human sacrifice]] in Nahua cultures, their warfare styles, particularly those of the Aztec and Maya, placed a premium on the capture of enemy warriors for live sacrifice. Advancement into the elite ''cuāuhocēlōtl'' warrior societies of the Aztec, for example, required taking 20 live captives from the battlefield. The macuahuitl thus shows several features designed to make it a useful tool for capturing prisoners: fitting spaced instead of contiguous blades, as seen in many codex illustrations, would intentionally limit the wound depth from a single blow, and the heavy wooden construction allows weakened opponents to be easily [[club (weapon)|clubbed]] unconscious with the flat side of the weapon. The art of disabling opponents using an un-bladed macuahuitl as a sparring club was taught from a young age in the Aztec [[Tēlpochcalli]] schools.<ref>Berdan and Anawalt, ''The Essential Codex Mendoza'', v. 2–4. UCal Press; 1997. Folio 62-R, p. 173.</ref>

The macuahuitl had many drawbacks in combat versus European steel swords. Despite being objectively sharper, prismatic obsidian is also considerably more [[brittle]] than steel; obsidian blades of the type used on the macuahuitl tended to shatter on impact with other obsidian blades, steel swords or [[plate armour]]. Obsidian blades also have difficulty penetrating European [[mail (armour)|mail]]. The thin, replaceable blades used on the macuahuitl were easily dulled or chipped by repeated impacts on bone or wood, making artful use of the weapon critical. It takes more time to lift and swing a club than it does to thrust with a sword. More space is needed as well, so warriors advanced in loose formations and fought in single combat.<ref>Townsend, 2000, p. 24</ref>

== Experimental archaeology ==
Replicas of the macuahuitl have been produced and tested against sides of beef for documentary shows on the History and Discovery channels, to demonstrate the effectiveness of this weapon. On the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History]] show ''[[Warriors (2009 TV series)|Warriors]]'', special forces operator and martial artist [[Terry Schappert]] injured himself while fencing with a macuahuitl; he cut the back of his left leg as the result of a back-swing motion.<ref>{{Citation |title="Warriors" Mayan Armageddon (TV Episode 2009) |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1407019/plotsummary |accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>

For [[SpikeTV]]'s reality program ''[[Deadliest Warrior]]'' a replica was created and tested against a model of a horse's head created using a horse's skeleton and [[ballistics gel]]. Actor and martial artist [[Éder Saúl López]] was able to decapitate the model, but it took three swings. Blows from the replica macuahuitl were most effective when it was swung and then dragged backwards upon impact, creating a sawing motion. This led [[Max Geiger]], the [[computer programmer]] of the series, to refer to the weapon as "the obsidian chainsaw". This may have been due to the crudely made obsidian cutting edges of the weapon used in the show, compared with more finely made prismatic obsidian blades, as in the Madrid specimen.<ref>{{Citation |last=Gonsalves |first=Kiran |title=Aztec Jaguar vs. Zande Warrior |date=11 May 2010 |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1643034/ |last2=Ojeda |first2=Michael S. |others=Cody Jones, Jay Charlot, Darell M. Davie |accessdate=29 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210050906/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1643034/ |archive-date=10 February 2017 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

