{{Infobox language |name=Taruma |nativename= |state=[[Guyana]], formerly Brazil |region=South of [[Aishalton]] |speakers=one family |dateprefix=as of&nbsp; |date=2009 |ref=<ref name=Carlin>Carlin 2011 (p. 11&nbsp;12)</ref> |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Katembri–Taruma languages|Katembri–Taruma]] ? |iso3=tdm |linglist=qoi |glotto=taru1236 |glottorefname=Taruma }}
'''Taruma''' (''Taruamá'') is a divergent language of northeastern Brazil. It has been reported to be extinct several times since as far back as 1770, but Eithne Carlin discovered the last speakers, and is documenting the language. It would seem that "Saluma" is the same language.
Taruma is unclassified.<ref name="Carlin" /> It has been proposed to be distantly related to [[Katembri language|Katembri]] (Kaufman 1990), but this relationship has not been repeated in recent surveys of South American languages (Campbell & Grondona 2012).
